flowchart LR

  subgraph INTENT["1. Path objective"]
    G1["Turn upstream RTDL state into decision posture that is safe to act on"]
    G2["Keep this path narrower than context formation, feature readiness, or decision formation itself"]
    G3["Answer whether the platform should proceed normally, hold back, or fail closed given the current dependency and health posture"]
  end

  subgraph ENTRY["2. Entry basis"]
    E1["The entry is not raw traffic and not raw context alone"]
    E2["The entry is the current RTDL truth surfaces that decisioning depends on"]
    E3["Those include joined-context readiness, feature readiness and freshness, projection health, checkpoint age, required-signal health, and run-scoped component participation"]
    E4["RTDL telemetry and proof posture explicitly require these surfaces: feature freshness and feature-ready counters, degrade-reason breakdown, run-scope adoption in every RTDL worker, and early fail-fast triggers when feature readiness stays dark or fail-closed spikes from an otherwise healthy upstream window"]
  end

  subgraph SPINE["5. Broad route logic"]
    R1["Current RTDL context, feature, and dependency signals"]
    R2["Guardrail classification logic"]
    R3["Decision posture truth"]
    R4["Downstream decision formation consumes that posture"]
    R5["Guardrail boundary stands between upstream RTDL truth and actual decision formation"]
  end

  subgraph CARRIES["4. What the path carries"]
    C1["Required-signal health from upstream RTDL components"]
    C2["Checkpoint and freshness posture"]
    C3["Dependency-availability posture"]
    C4["Run-scoped component participation"]
    C5["Typed reasons why a component is healthy, advisory, stale, or insufficient"]
    C6["The guardrail has emitted concrete posture such as decision_mode = NORMAL with required signals OK"]
    C7["In other proofs it has flipped to FAIL_CLOSED with explicit reason like required_signal_gap:ofp_health"]
    C8["So the path carries typed dependency posture, not just binary health pings"]
  end

  subgraph LOGIC["6. Logical design reading"]
    L1["The platform treats degrade and insufficiency judgment as first-class runtime truth, not as a side effect of decision formation"]
    L2["The system is not saying if the feature or entity surfaces look odd, decisioning will just figure it out"]
    L3["There is a dedicated guardrail that distinguishes true dependency outage from semantic-quality advisory and benign lag"]
    L4["It only fails closed when the runtime really lacks sufficient trusted inputs"]
    L5["That is exactly the distinction the guardrail definition insists on"]
  end

  subgraph SEATING["7. Concrete seating in the current wired system"]
    S1["The copied baseline wired graphs show active degrade-ladder deployment inside the RTDL namespace alongside context, entity, feature, decision, action, and audit surfaces"]
    S2["The degrade ladder hands adjudication input to the decision surface"]
    S3["The handles registry keeps an explicit runtime deployment reference for the degrade-ladder surface"]
    S4["So the guardrail is concrete runtime workload in the live RTDL plane, not just a conceptual box"]
  end

  subgraph RATIONALE["8. Why the design looks like this"]
    Y1["The platform deliberately refuses to let raw component health or stale artifacts decide safety posture directly"]
    Y2["When replay-era watermark signals made projector health look red even while current-run mutation and checkpoints were healthy, the fix was not to treat all red surfaces as hard failure"]
    Y3["The guardrail recovered to NORMAL with required signals OK"]
    Y4["Later, when coupled proof genuinely hit required_signal_gap:ofp_health, the guardrail flipped to FAIL_CLOSED and the blocker was treated as real"]
    Y5["That is the desired behavior: advisories stay advisories, insufficiency becomes fail-closed, and the distinction is explicit"]
  end

  subgraph CONTRACT["9. What larger contracts are shaping this path"]
    X1["The path is shaped by the larger RTDL contract rather than by local convenience"]
    X2["Each RTDL component must be semantically correct, time-correct, replay-safe, observable, and explainable"]
    X3["For the guardrail specifically: it must distinguish outage from advisory, fail closed only on real insufficiency, avoid sticky false-red from stale artifacts, and recover promptly when dependencies recover"]
    X4["The RTDL proof plan turns that into concrete focus metrics such as false fail-closed rate and degrade-reason breakdown"]
  end

  subgraph TRADEOFFS["10. Trade-offs and constraints"]
    T1["This path deliberately adds another explicit boundary to the RTDL graph"]
    T2["That costs complexity because the system has to maintain and explain upstream health semantics, the guardrail's own classification logic, and the difference between upstream red artifact and true decision-blocking insufficiency"]
    T3["But that complexity buys something important"]
    T4["Decision formation no longer has to invent its own safety posture from scattered upstream clues"]
    T5["The platform can explain why it proceeded, stayed normal, or failed closed"]
    T6["Without this boundary, replay-watermark advisories and genuine feature-health gaps would be much easier to confuse"]
  end

  subgraph NECESSITY["11. Necessity test"]
    N1["If this path is removed, the platform can still ingest traffic, build projections, materialize features, and produce decisions"]
    N2["But it loses a clean answer to whether the runtime had sufficient trusted inputs at decision time"]
    N3["It loses a clean answer to whether an upstream issue was merely advisory or genuinely blocking"]
    N4["It loses a clean answer to why the run failed closed"]
    N5["It loses a clean answer to whether decision formation is failing because the inputs are unsafe or because the guardrail boundary does not exist"]
    N6["That would weaken A immediately because the platform would have no explicit owner for the most important question between feature truth exists and decision is allowed"]
  end

  subgraph CLOSURE["3. Owned outcome and 12. What this path proves for A"]
    O1["Adjudicated decision mode for the current run and current event posture"]
    O2["Trustworthy answer to whether downstream decisioning should proceed normally or treat the current posture as insufficiently trusted"]
    O3["Concrete posture has been emitted, such as NORMAL with required signals OK or FAIL_CLOSED with explicit reason"]
    O4["Owned outcome: decision posture truth"]
    A1["Purpose claim:<br/>the platform has a distinct job for adjudicating dependency posture before decisioning proceeds"]
    A2["Intentionality claim:<br/>advisories, insufficiency, and fail-closed are deliberately separated rather than collapsed into one crude red/green status"]
    A3["Materialization claim:<br/>the degrade ladder is concrete live runtime workload in the current RTDL plane"]
    A4["Contract claim:<br/>this path is governed by explicit requirements around false fail-closed, dependency classification correctness, recovery-to-normal, and decision-mode stability"]
    A5["Constraint-awareness claim:<br/>the system already knows this boundary can be semantically tricky, which is why the implementation trail keeps distinguishing replay advisory, feature-health insufficiency, and proof-harness defects rather than calling all of them the same thing"]
    A6["A-level meaning:<br/>the platform has an explicit owner for whether runtime truth is sufficiently trusted for decisioning to proceed"]
  end

